00:40:28,421 --> 00:40:31,404
I started with the belt sander because it was one of the safer tools, but in time I

690
00:40:31,444 --> 00:40:31,945
learned them all.

691
00:40:31,965 --> 00:40:34,888
We had a shop smith, which you can see at the left.

692
00:40:34,928 --> 00:40:38,212
It's a big motor, it slides along these metal rails and they make all these attachments

693
00:40:38,272 --> 00:40:38,532
for it.

694
00:40:39,133 --> 00:40:43,678
A bandsaw, a lathe, a drill press, a jigsaw, basically any wood tool you can imagine you

695
00:40:43,698 --> 00:40:45,080
can get as a shop smith attachment.

696
00:40:45,981 --> 00:40:48,323
And they last forever, which is why the company is now out of business.

697
00:40:51,395 --> 00:40:54,896
So I learned them one by one, you know, I'd draw little snaking lines on wood with pencil

698
00:40:54,936 --> 00:40:56,956
and practice tracing them on the bandsaw.

699
00:40:56,996 --> 00:41:01,237
I'd learn how to hold a chisel against a wood blank when it was turning in the lathe, you

700
00:41:01,257 --> 00:41:04,238
know, learning the right motor speed for each tool, learning how to care for them, how to

701
00:41:04,298 --> 00:41:05,078
fix them when they broke.

702
00:41:06,679 --> 00:41:09,159
And along the way I learned to really respect the tools and their power.

703
00:41:09,199 --> 00:41:12,120
I still remember the sound the bandsaw made when you turned it on.

704
00:41:12,640 --> 00:41:16,921
You flip the switch on the motor, it's this really loud metal clack, and then this kind

705
00:41:16,941 --> 00:41:19,722
of whining, pitching noise as the saw blade spins up.

706
00:41:21,166 --> 00:41:23,908
No matter how many times I used it, at that noise,

707
00:41:23,928 --> 00:41:26,749
I always felt the slightest twinge of fear when it started.

708
00:41:27,270 --> 00:41:28,730
But it was good because it kept me alert

709
00:41:28,770 --> 00:41:29,911
and made sure I was paying attention.

710
00:41:32,192 --> 00:41:33,933
Along the way, I also learned great respect

711
00:41:33,973 --> 00:41:35,634
and even love for the wood itself.

712
00:41:36,495 --> 00:41:38,456
Just six months ago, I made these tables

713
00:41:38,516 --> 00:41:40,637
out of black walnut in my backyard in Seattle.

714
00:41:41,558 --> 00:41:44,039
I spent probably 100 or 200 hours surfacing

715
00:41:44,079 --> 00:41:46,080
and finishing the wood, and almost all of that time

716
00:41:46,120 --> 00:41:48,522
was between me and a simple block plane

717
00:41:48,982 --> 00:41:50,223
or hand sander in the wood.

718
00:41:51,139 --> 00:41:55,062
I made a few initial cuts with a table saw, but other than that I did everything with hand tools.

719
00:41:56,763 --> 00:41:59,986
I got to know every subtle curve in the surface of each table.

720
00:42:00,727 --> 00:42:04,329
Each plank was different with a unique beauty in the grain and edge.

721
00:42:05,270 --> 00:42:08,973
And I look back on those hours as a collaboration between the wood and me,

722
00:42:09,053 --> 00:42:12,576
working together to bring out the potential in that grain and to make something beautiful.

723
00:42:16,359 --> 00:42:17,720
It takes craft to make art.

724
00:42:19,033 --> 00:42:22,654
It takes skill with any medium and any tool set to make something beautiful.

725
00:42:23,454 --> 00:42:25,955
And communication is a craft just like any other in every way,

726
00:42:27,155 --> 00:42:27,815
except for one.

727
00:42:30,775 --> 00:42:34,876
In craft and in art, we are accustomed to being the craftspeople and the artists.

728
00:42:35,896 --> 00:42:38,117
But in human relationships, we are also the medium.

729
00:42:39,757 --> 00:42:40,597
We shape each other.

730
00:42:41,477 --> 00:42:42,417
We work on each other.

731
00:42:43,618 --> 00:42:45,498
We can help to smooth off each other's rough edges.

732
00:42:45,778 --> 00:42:48,458
And with great skill and enough care, we can refine one another.

733
00:42:49,284 --> 00:42:52,227
We can help to bring out the beauty and potential that exists within each of us.

734
00:42:54,049 --> 00:42:56,551
But through misuse we can and we all do harm one another.

735
00:42:56,811 --> 00:42:59,654
And so when we meet someone who uses these tools consciously,

736
00:43:00,114 --> 00:43:03,518
our reaction is suspicion, is apprehension.

737
00:43:05,419 --> 00:43:09,984
And this is as it should be. Fear is a normal reaction to a situation that could cause us harm.

738
00:43:11,585 --> 00:43:12,766
The fear is not the problem.

739
00:43:13,627 --> 00:43:15,469
The problem is when we let that fear stop us.

740
00:43:17,738 --> 00:43:21,259
The proper response to fear is gratitude, is appreciation.

741
00:43:23,520 --> 00:43:28,001
Appreciation that it's there to warn you about danger. Appreciation that it's keeping you alert.

742
00:43:29,221 --> 00:43:33,922
And then after that, the proper response is to continue to act just with extraordinary care.

743
00:43:35,723 --> 00:43:39,523
A life lived in the shadow of fear is one where we misunderstand what the fear is telling us.

744
00:43:40,652 --> 00:43:45,694
With communication, we misunderstand when we think the fear is telling us that the tools themselves are evil,

745
00:43:46,014 --> 00:43:48,056
or the people who use them are villainous.

746
00:43:49,156 --> 00:43:49,656
It is not.

747
00:43:51,037 --> 00:43:52,918
It is simply letting us know that we need to be careful.

748
00:43:59,001 --> 00:44:00,302
The skill of communication,

749
00:44:01,463 --> 00:44:03,904
and the knowledge that comes from analyzing human interactions,

750
00:44:03,944 --> 00:44:06,285
these things are tools that we can use to do great things.

751
00:44:07,426 --> 00:44:09,647
If we let our fear dissuade us from using them at all.

752
00:44:10,054 --> 00:44:11,596
we forfeit the chance to do that good.

753
00:44:13,437 --> 00:44:17,341
Okay, you ask, but what about those people we all know who do use these tools to do harm?

754
00:44:17,381 --> 00:44:21,204
Who use them for their own personal material gain at the expense of others?

755
00:44:23,266 --> 00:44:26,449
I think it's easy to feel anger and contempt for these people, and when we have to work

756
00:44:26,489 --> 00:44:28,931
directly with them we can feel threatened, we can feel upset.

757
00:44:30,192 --> 00:44:32,234
But perhaps we should instead feel compassion.

758
00:44:34,816 --> 00:44:35,797
When we learn a craft,

759
00:44:36,945 --> 00:44:40,928
Every moment of that learning is an opportunity to open our eyes to great beauty.

760
00:44:41,488 --> 00:44:43,490
When I was a child and I didn't know anything about woodworking,

761
00:44:43,790 --> 00:44:46,472
I'd look at a piece of furniture, all I would see was the utility.

762
00:44:46,892 --> 00:44:49,333
This one's for holding books, that one's for holding clothes.

763
00:44:51,154 --> 00:44:53,076
Practicing woodworking opened my eyes.

764
00:44:53,176 --> 00:44:57,719
Now I look at furniture and I see the utility but also the care and the craftsmanship.

765
00:44:58,559 --> 00:45:02,061
The beauty of the wood itself and even like a little camaraderie for the person who made it,

766
00:45:02,102 --> 00:45:04,103
knowing, oh, this section must have been really difficult.

767
00:45:04,712 --> 00:45:07,373
or being able to admire the quality of a specific joint.

768
00:45:08,574 --> 00:45:11,475
That appreciation, that ability to encounter something

769
00:45:12,035 --> 00:45:14,697
and see not just the outer surface of the thing, but also the time

770
00:45:15,117 --> 00:45:17,838
and care and love that it's made of. That

771
00:45:18,158 --> 00:45:21,279
is our sensitivity to all of the beauty and joy and love in the world.

772
00:45:24,281 --> 00:45:27,542
There is one catch. Our practice will teach us nothing

773
00:45:27,842 --> 00:45:30,544
unless we bring our attention to those moments. We have to be willing to see.

774
00:45:31,124 --> 00:45:34,445
We have to let the experience change us. If we practice carelessly...

775
00:45:35,202 --> 00:45:36,383
then our eyes remain closed.

776
00:45:36,663 --> 00:45:41,187
And so while it's frustrating to see a skilled communicator who uses his words to harm or

777
00:45:41,247 --> 00:45:47,411
climb ladders to earn a bonus at someone else's expense, when my mind is open I look at a

778
00:45:47,451 --> 00:45:48,752
person like that and it breaks my heart.

779
00:45:51,454 --> 00:45:55,737
To have such skill with words, he must have practiced for so long.

780
00:45:57,078 --> 00:46:02,743
And the whole time he had such opportunity to see the beauty in other people, to see

781
00:46:02,763 --> 00:46:03,643
the beauty in himself.

782
00:46:05,172 --> 00:46:06,894
and the joy in relationships, but he didn't.

783
00:46:08,696 --> 00:46:10,958
You can't explain those things to someone who doesn't see them.

784
00:46:10,998 --> 00:46:13,601
It's like trying to explain color to someone who's been blind from birth.

785
00:46:15,863 --> 00:46:17,104
So he doesn't even know what he's missing.

786
00:46:18,906 --> 00:46:20,307
He thinks the goal is acquisition.

787
00:46:22,029 --> 00:46:24,631
Tries to fill his life with material wealth because that's all he knows.

788
00:46:31,143 --> 00:46:36,024
If you find yourself working with someone like this, I might humbly suggest a little meditation to develop compassion for him.

789
00:46:36,064 --> 00:46:42,526
And it goes like this, when we do not know happiness, and we try to fill its void with pleasure, we suffer.

790
00:46:47,348 --> 00:46:54,810
Okay, so if communication and the study of human interaction is a craft that opens our eyes, what exactly does it open our eyes to?

791
00:46:56,571 --> 00:46:59,071
Well, just like woodworking taught me deeply the nature of wood.

792
00:46:59,833 --> 00:47:02,615
Communication deeply teaches us the true nature of people.

793
00:47:03,116 --> 00:47:05,597
And the more we know something, the more genuinely we're able to love it.

794
00:47:08,019 --> 00:47:13,643
At the end of the day, I think some of our aversion to this analysis is subconsciously part of us doesn't want to see our true nature.

795
00:47:14,203 --> 00:47:16,785
We don't like the idea that we can be manipulated.

796
00:47:17,005 --> 00:47:19,687
That someone else can trick us with a simple wording of a question.

797
00:47:21,288 --> 00:47:24,811
We want to believe that our preferences are rational and well considered,

798
00:47:25,491 --> 00:47:27,072
and that our behavior is governed by reason.

799
00:47:29,794 --> 00:47:30,934
But these things are not true.

800
00:47:32,075 --> 00:47:35,276
And believing them does us no more good than it would a woodworker to pretend that wood

801
00:47:35,296 --> 00:47:37,376
does not burn or cannot be broken.

802
00:47:40,377 --> 00:47:43,798
We are creatures, you and I, and these are our vulnerabilities.

803
00:47:46,539 --> 00:47:50,700
We are afraid of vulnerability, but it is the truth of our nature, and only by acknowledging

804
00:47:50,760 --> 00:47:52,361
it can we truly love one another.

805
00:47:53,981 --> 00:47:57,522
The more we practice, the more we start to see just how much of our interaction with

806
00:47:57,542 --> 00:47:58,202
each other every day

807
00:47:58,643 --> 00:48:03,466
Are these ways of staying safe, you know, they're nothing but boilerplate, habit, neurosis,

808
00:48:04,187 --> 00:48:08,270
polite strategies for saying the right things but keeping our distance.

809
00:48:08,330 --> 00:48:10,171
We greet one another and we converse.

810
00:48:10,271 --> 00:48:13,893
But if we aren't really present, it's like our words are just kind of read off a script.

811
00:48:15,675 --> 00:48:19,597
The power of this work is that seeing gives us a choice.

812
00:48:19,638 --> 00:48:21,779
We can choose not to give the boilerplate response.

813
00:48:21,819 --> 00:48:23,560
We can choose to respond with sincerity.

814
00:48:24,481 --> 00:48:25,382
We can choose connection.

815
00:48:26,629 --> 00:48:28,952
And that's why I believe so strongly in the value of this work.

816
00:48:30,454 --> 00:48:32,577
I hope something I've said this afternoon has been helpful to you.

817
00:48:32,717 --> 00:48:33,578
Thank you very much for coming.

